foia:ProcessedRequestSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of pending requests in the beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY17 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending case for Office "A" at the end of FY17, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY18, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A".

foia:ProcessedAppealSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of pending appeals in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal initially assigned to Office "A" in FY17 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending appeal for Office "A" at the end of FY17, but when Office "B" closes the appeal in FY18, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A".

foia:ProcessedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of requests received is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: a request initially assigned to Office "A" in FY17 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending case for Office "A" at the end of FY17, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY18, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A".

foia:BackloggedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: After reviewing its database, ED adjusted the number of backlogged requests as of the end of the fiscal year.
The discrepancy in the number of backlogged requests pending in FY17 is due to a program error in the case management system.

foia:ProcessedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of received appeals in beginning of fiscal year for the components is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal initially assigned to Office "A" in FY17 is later assigned to Office "B" would show as a pending case for Office "A" at the end of FY17, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY18, the report will show Office "B" as the pending office at the start of FY17 rather than Office "A".

foia:BackloggedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: The discrepancy in the number of backlog appeals pending in FY17 is due to how cases are tracked within our case management system. Example: an appeal received initially to Office "A" in FY17 is latter assigned to Office "B" would show as a backlog for Office "A" at the end of Fy17, but when Office "B" closes the case in FY18, the report will show Office "B" as the backlog office at the start of FY18 rather than Office "A."
